#regroup ethnicity types: asian, black, hispanic, white, others 
lev_e <- c("ASIAN", "BLACK", "HISPANIC", "WHITE", "OTHERS")
heart$ethnicities <- factor(rep(NA, nrow(heart)), order = F, levels = lev_e)
heart$ethnicities[heart$ethnicity == "PATIENT DECLINED TO ANSWER" | 
                  heart$ethnicity == "UNABLE TO OBTAIN"|
                  heart$ethnicity == "UNKNOWN/NOT SPECIFIED"] <- NA
heart$ethnicities[heart$ethnicity == "ASIAN"| 
                  heart$ethnicity == "ASIAN - ASIAN INDIAN" |
                  heart$ethnicity == "ASIAN - CAMBODIAN" |
                  heart$ethnicity == "ASIAN - CHINESE" |
                  heart$ethnicity == "ASIAN - VIETNAMESE"] <- "ASIAN"

heart$ethnicities[heart$ethnicity == "BLACK/AFRICAN AMERICAN"| 
                    heart$ethnicity == "BLACK/CAPE VERDEAN" |
                    heart$ethnicity == "BLACK/HAITIAN"] <- "BLACK"

heart$ethnicities[heart$ethnicity == "HISPANIC/LATINO - CUBAN" |
                    heart$ethnicity == "HISPANIC OR LATINO" |
                    heart$ethnicity == "HISPANIC/LATINO - CUBAN"] <- "HISPANIC"

heart$ethnicities[heart$ethnicity == "PORTUGUESE" |
                    heart$ethnicity == "WHITE" |
                    heart$ethnicity == "WHITE - BRAZILIAN" |
                    heart$ethnicity == "WHITE - OTHER EUROPEAN" |
                    heart$ethnicity == "WHITE - RUSSIAN"] <- "WHITE"

heart$ethnicities[heart$ethnicity == "MIDDLE EASTERN" |
                    heart$ethnicity == "MULTI RACE ETHNICITY" |
                    heart$ethnicity == "NATIVE HAWAIIAN OR OTHER PACIFIC ISLANDER" |
                    heart$ethnicity == "OTHER"] <- "OTHERS"

The purpose of this project is to utilize data extracted out from MIMIC III to train models and predict our desired outcome. Our team chose to investigate in premature health attacks- looking into patients who are younger than 65 that got admitted into the hospital due to heart attacks. We were interested in looking into factors such as age, icu length of stay, weight, height, cholesterol levels and many more. The first issue we faced was that once we obtained the mimic III dataset, there are lots of NAs for multiple variables. As a result, I had to remove many variables that would have played important roles in predicting patients’ mortalities such as height, weight, heart rate and cholesterol levels. For the data cleaning part, I decided to re-level the ethnicities: instead of having over 20 different levels, I concentrated it down to 5: Asian, Black, White, Hispanic and Others. I also renamed the expire_flag levels from 0 and 1 to no and yes. Upon further investigation, several variables were removed as well if it contains more than 20% NAs. A correlation plot is produced to get an idea of what variables might be strongly correlated to our predictor variable- expire_flag, and nothing really popped into significance. Data visualizations have shown that there are more males than females in the dataset, and the race of the patients is predominantly white. For data modeling, I tried multiple methods including logistic regression, SVM classifier with linear, poly and rbf kernel, decision tree and random forest. Overall, the results are not too great, and the performance between each method is not significantly different. Simple logistic regression actually outperformed SVM linear and SVM poly by 1%. SVM Radial performed slightly better than linear and poly kernel, but the difference is approximately 1% as well. Most models gave higher specificity than sensitivity- indicating that the true negative rate is higher than the true positive rate. At the end, random forest provided the best result with accuracy rate up to 70.8%, sensitivity 64.4% and specificity at 72.3 %. Decision tree is the second-best performer with accuracy rate of 68.3%. These models didn’t perform well in predicting patients mortality rate can be due to the fact that we were unable to include important factors such as weight, cholesterol level and heart rate. At the end, we were left with variables that are usable, but these variables might not be highly related to heart attacks.

Logistic: 0.658 SVM Linear: 0.648 SVM poly: 0.648 SVM Radial: 0.655 Decision tree: 0.683 Random forest: 0.708
